<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-453-030  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 453 030.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  July 24 1989 v10 n29 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Gov't split over PC ban. (microcomputer exports to Soviet bloccountries)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Thyfault, Mary E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US microcomputer manufacturers may soon be allowed to exportpreviously restricted computer technology to the Soviet Union andother Eastern bloc nations due to a ruling by the US Dept ofCommerce.andP;  The decision, which declares that mid-range systems arefreely available from other countries, opens the way for therelaxation of export controls over older IBM Corp ATs and clones.andO;Effected are the IBM Personal System/2 and the Apple MacIntoshPlus and SE models, desktop models employing the Intel Corp 286 16MHz microprocessor, with up to 4Mbytes of RAM.andP;  Machines with 386chips or laptop models are not affected.andP;  The decision wassupported by both the Computer and Communications Industry Assoc(CCIA) and the Coordinating Committee on Multilateral ExportControls (COCOM), an organization of 17 western nations.andP;  The movewas opposed by the Dept of Defense.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government RegulationInternational TradeComputer IndustrySoviet UnionUnited States. Department of CommerceTechnology TransferTechnologyComputer and Communications Industry AssociationCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export Controls.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>